judge said discriminated
against minorities, would
benefit black Americans.

27:20.606 --> 27:26.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Our job is not to
make life
more comfortable for the violent
disrupter,

27:26.144 --> 27:31.750 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
but to make life more
comfortable for the
African- American parent trying
to raise their

27:31.783 --> 27:33.519 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
kids in peace.

27:33.552 --> 27:38.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: World peace with was
the topic
of a letter from 75 retired
career diplomats

27:38.123 --> 27:42.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
slamming Trump as entirely
unqualified to
serve as president.

27:43.028 --> 27:47.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most of the diplomats who signed
the letter
haven't been publicly associated
with politics.

27:47.666 --> 27:53.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, a Politico analysis
of campaign
finance reports found that the
Trump campaign

27:53.772 --> 27:58.477 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has paid Trump's businesses $8.2
million.

27:58.510 --> 28:02.014 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's about 7 percent of the
campaign's total
spending.

28:02.047 --> 28:06.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hillary Clinton spent the day
behind closed
doors preparing for Monday
night's debate.

28:06.885 --> 28:10.055 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That left running mate Tim Kaine
as the campaign's
top messenger.

28:10.088 --> 28:11.890 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

28:11.924 --> 28:13.759 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
TIM KAINE (D-VA), Vice
Presidential Candidate:
Where we see challenges all over
the country,

28:13.792 --> 28:19.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
challenges of gulfs and gaps
that exist between
communities and law enforcement,
we have got

28:19.932 --> 28:21.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to put them on the table.

28:21.400 --> 28:26.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're not easy, but we can do
that with
a calm and peaceful spirit.

28:26.305 --> 28:31.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Clinton also reached
out to millennial
voters, appearing on the new
installment of

28:31.810 --> 28:38.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
comic Zach Galifianakis' Web
series "Between
Two Ferns" that went online this
morning.

28:38.717 --> 28:41.386 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm John
Yang.

28:41.420 --> 28:46.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: There's been no
shortage of
attention paid to who might win
the presidential

28:46.158 --> 28:51.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
election this November, but what
promises
can they deliver once in office?

28:51.196 --> 28:56.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we examine what the
early days of
a Trump presidency might look
like, and whether

28:56.168 --> 28:59.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the next Congress would be an
ally or a thorn
in his side.

28:59.905 --> 29:05.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For that, we turn to Evan Osnos,
a staff writer
for "The New Yorker" magazine,
and Seung Min

29:05.410 --> 29:06.378 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Kim.

29:06.411 --> 29:08.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She's a congressional reporter
for Politico.

29:08.413 --> 29:09.848 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And welcome to both of you.

29:09.881 --> 29:11.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Evan, I'm going to start with
you.

29:11.650 --> 29:14.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You did write a sort a story for
the latest
"New Yorker" about what Trump
would do in

29:15.020 --> 29:17.289 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
his early days in office.

29:17.322 --> 29:18.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Let's go down the list.

29:19.024 --> 29:24.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You start with suggesting he
would renounce
this global agreement on climate
change.

29:24.730 --> 29:25.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How would that work?

29:25.731 --> 29:27.499 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What could he do?

29:27.532 --> 29:29.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVAN OSNOS, "The New Yorker":
Well, the campaign
is preparing what's been
described as the

29:29.468 --> 29:34.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
first day project, which would
be an effort
to try to do a large number of
things right

29:34.806 --> 29:38.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
away using the powers of the
executive office,
using the powers of the
presidency.

29:38.877 --> 29:40.579 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're planning on 25 things.

29:40.612 --> 29:44.416 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, if they started, for
instance, one of
the ones that they are weighing
is to renounce

29:44.449 --> 29:45.717 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Paris climate change.

29:45.751 --> 29:47.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That -- the president has legal
authority
to do it.

29:48.020 --> 29:54.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's much the way that George W.
Bush when
he came into office in 2001 was
able to, for

29:54.693 --> 29:58.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
instance, remove the United
States from an
agreement on the International
Criminal Court.

29:58.196 --> 30:01.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is nothing that stops a
president from
doing that.

30:01.166 --> 30:03.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they could also do other
things.

30:03.035 --> 30:07.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For instance, he could roll back
some environmental
regulations that have been
imposed by the

30:07.706 --> 30:14.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obama administration, and he
could also redirect
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms

30:14.246 --> 30:20.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to say you no longer need to
deliver background
-- to do background checks on
gun purchases

30:20.118 --> 30:21.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the way that you were directed
to do so under
Obama.

30:21.953 --> 30:27.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So he could take
some substantive
steps in the early days that
wouldn't require

30:27.159 --> 30:28.460 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
any congressional action.

30:28.493 --> 30:30.595 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Seung Min, let me return to you.

30:30.629 --> 30:34.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the assumption has been,
if Donald
Trump wins, he is probably going
to keep a

30:34.266 --> 30:37.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Republican Senate and a
Republican House.

30:37.936 --> 30:42.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if he makes moves like this,
the presumption
is, there is not going to be
much pushback

30:42.541 --> 30:44.009 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
from the Hill.

30:44.042 --> 30:47.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEUNG MIN KIM, Politico: It
depends on the
form of his proposals make.

30:47.746 --> 30:51.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The executive order action part
of this is
really interesting, because what
you have

30:51.516 --> 30:55.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
heard from Republicans and here
in Congress
for the last several years is,
they're basically

30:55.420 --> 31:00.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
calling President Obama the
imperial president,
that he has acted too much on
his own without

31:00.525 --> 31:02.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the will of the Congress to
accomplish his
agenda.

31:02.994 --> 31:07.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a lot of these goals perhaps
on climate,
environmental issues, a
President Donald Trump

31:07.833 --> 31:11.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
may share with Republicans in
Congress.

31:11.536 --> 31:15.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if they don't, it will be
interesting
to see what they -- what their
response is

31:15.373 --> 31:20.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to how a President Trump deals
with kind of
the executive powers -- or the
powers of the

31:20.445 --> 31:22.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
executive branch.

31:22.314 --> 31:24.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Evan, one other
thing we know,
one of the many things Donald
Trump has talked

31:25.016 --> 31:28.220 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about is suspending the Syrian
refugee program.

31:28.253 --> 31:31.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president has been talking
about increasing
that number to over 100,000.

31:31.723 --> 31:33.492 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is it that Trump is looking
at doing?

31:33.525 --> 31:36.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVAN OSNOS: Trump is -- Trump's
advisers have
told me that they're considering
on day one

